<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by The Welsh Local Government Association (WLGA)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by The Welsh Local Government Association (WLGA)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Welsh Local Government Association (WLGA) represents the 22 local authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, and the three national park authorities, the three fire and rescue authorities, and four police authorities are associate members.  It seeks to provide representation to local authorities within an emerging policy framework that satisfies the key priorities of our members and delivers a broad range of services that add value to Welsh Local Government and the communities they serve.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The aspiration of a welfare system that is simpler, makes work pay, lifts people out of poverty, combats </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">worklessness</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> and reduces the national debt burden is welcomed.  However, the approach </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> welfare reform and particularly the progress with implementation of Universal Credit (UC) is of major concern.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The UK Government</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">continues to make radical reforms </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to the welfare system which the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">WLGA</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> believes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">has the potential to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> adversely affect </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the most vulnerable in our society</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> a reserved matter, UK Government to date has shown little understanding of the added dimension that the devolved government arrangement in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> brings to a complex landscape of service delivery.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Local authorities have spent many years redesigning locally delivered services designed around the customer and absorbed the service demands driven by their needs.  Welfare reform is designed around the need to reduce the national welfare budget.  It is not designed around the needs of the most vulnerable members of society and we are fearful about the potential social impact. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The focus of our response sets out our concerns of the plan to include housing costs within Universal Credit.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mitigating the risk to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the Universal Credit Programme</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The progress with the UC programme to date has been mixed. Limited progress has been made in testing some of the key propositions through pilot initiatives for a limited range of potential UC client groups e.g. direct payments demonstration projects, LA led pilots </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">(financial inclusion and digital delivery), UC pathfinders (across a narrow client group) dealing with only 1,000 claims (April – July ’13). A limited number of these cases have had their housing costs included as part of their UC award.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Serious concerns with progress of UC were raised by the Major Project Authority earlier this year which led to the programme reset and more recently the National Audit Office has identified serious concerns with the progress with the UC programme in relation to:-</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Programme management short-comings</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Progress against plans (including IT)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:20.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is our contention that removing/deferring the housing cost element from UC at the outset will significantly reduce the scope of the project allowing DWP to re-focus resources on the remaining elements of the project that fall under its direct control. This has the added benefit of allowing LAs to deliver aspects of UC in isolation e.g. direct payments to social housing tenants. Housing costs could then be included at a later date once the IT development of the UC system is ready to include this element.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.18pt; padding-left:13.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We are of the opinion that deferring or removing housing costs from UC design will significantly de-risk the project, in the short and medium term. It is important to stress that this is not about ‘self-preservation’ for LAs, but ensuring continuity of high quality services for customers and landlords. Such an approach may increase the likelihood of UC being successfully implemented.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We believe that removing /deferring housing costs from UC delivers the following project benefits:-</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Simplifies system design – both administratively and from an IT perspective</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Reduces the requirements to deliver and setup the Local Support Services Framework in a short period of time, where there are currently concerns relating to requirements and funding availability.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Reduces level of reliance on local government to deliver the safe-landing of UC, however this may help promote further close working between DWP/HMRC &amp; LA’s</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Removes many of the data-sharing issues in the short term.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Minimises the impact of direct payment through implementation in a controlled environment outside of UC (with the benefit of safeguarding income streams for landlords , and minimising rent arrears</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Reducing the potential impact on homelessness, and</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Reduct</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ion </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in the level of DWP resources involved in the project – hence reduced project costs</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Support Service Framework</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Concerns remain about the lack of clarity in local authorities’ role in provision of support and advice of UC.  The DWP are committed to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">including LAs in the face to face (F2F) delivery of UC.  The draft Local Support Services Framework sets out how this will operate, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">although funding arrangements for organisations involved in delivery are not yet clear.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">LAs are currently planning for the ultimate loss of Housing Benefit administration and the consequential loss of staff and associated assets. In order to prevent the removal of physical infrastructure that would be needed to assist in the delivery of UC, the DWP need to commit to either (a) removing housing costs completely from UC, or (b) utilising former HB staff to assist in the implementation of UC. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is important to reference the potential impact that budget cuts affecting LAs as a result of the 2013 Spending Round may have in the longer term. The scale of the budget cuts may result in the closure/removal of the existing property infrastructure e.g. customer service centres, libraries, all of which may be required to help deliver the customer facing aspects of UC (both F2F and digital delivery). Therefore, by the stage that LSSF arrangements are concluded, some LAs may not be in a position to participate in the new arrangements due to decisions taken to close some of its property portfolio.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Simplification of service delivery</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Local authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> have a long track record of efficient and effective service delivery </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in b</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">enefit services </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">and staff involved have a wealth of expertise and experience in dealing with housing related matters e.g. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the complexities of housing related costs</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">determining commercial tenancies/contrived tenancies</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">determining eligible service charges and management costs</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">dealing with supported, exempt and temporary accommodation</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The functionality of existing HB computer systems already deal with a diverse range of housing related issues (there is already sunk investment). If housing costs are included within UC, this functionality will have to be re-designed into UC computer system - at additional cost. It is accepted by DWP personnel working on the UC project that housing costs are the most complex benefit which needs to be absorbed into UC.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The DWP is currently trying to finalise proposals for supported/exempt accommodation and temporary accommodation, some of which will remain with LAs for payment. The WLGA has concerns that without proper IT development and data capture there remains significant scope for duplicate payments to be made from LA’s and DWP in respect of UC housing costs due to incorrect information being held on systems. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">This possibility for error could further extend to fraud and abuse through contrived and non-commercial tenancy arrangements being created as UC will have access to the same level of information as LAs regarding properties, occupants and landlords. Existing arrangements of cross-checking of information limits the scope for fraudulent claims to be made.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Monthly Payments</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Many </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">HB </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">customers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> are used to having </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">payment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s on a 4-weekly frequency under LHA rules. The extensive experience that LAs have in educating customers in the private rented sector in the transition to ‘monthly’ payments can be used to assist the remaining customers in the social rented sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As part of the Welfare Reform programme, demonstration projects have been setup whereby the customer’s HB is paid directly to the tenant instead of the landlord.  Clear evidence about the cost of administration across these initiatives have not been made available to the local government community, but there are doubts over the cost effectiveness of the work undertaken</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">. As with the LHA direct payments LAs could replicate this process across the social rented sector at a significantly reduced cost.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Such an approach would utilise the experience of LAs outlined in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> above, and could be achieved without exposing LAs (as landlords) or other social landlords to the risk of non-payment of rent that including housing costs in UC would inevitably bring. The WLGA suggests that this could be introduced on a phased basis by local authorities, with an automatic default </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">on new claims </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">to be paid directly to the tenant and not the landlord</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">This could then be extended to include changes of circumstances, so the caseload gradually moves to direct payment, achieving the UK Government’s policy objective.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Any risk of non-payment of rent will be managed as in the private rented sector thereby controlling the risk of homelessness. </span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The WLGA suggests that in the UC business plan and overall programme, the volume of queries it would receive from landlords of tenants in relation to queries of housing costs payments has been under-estimated, notwithstanding the overlap with the award of Discretionary Housing Payments once a claim for UC has been decided.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Data</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> S</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">haring</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">With the introduction of CTRS in April 2013, specific provisions had to be made with the design of CTRS schemes to net off any housing cost element from the UC calculation. This approach is needed for consistency with the existing approach of netting off housing benefit, as without this adjustment many applicants income will be calculated at a rate that will adversely affect their entitlement to CTRS. Discussions are on-going between DWP and Welsh Government about how this data will be provided to LAs by UC.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">This complexity of data-sharing and the interaction with CTRS will be removed if housing costs are removed from UC and remain with LA’s.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Fraud and Error</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The proposed change of approach within the UC Programme would maintain some stability to local authorities in the short term, whilst allowing DWP to ensure that the core UC system IT is working and able to incorporate Housing Costs moving forward. It is accepted by DWP staff working on the UC Programme Design that incorporating Housing Costs into the UC system is causing the greatest issue because of the complexity involved; the scope for error to occur is therefore greater and has the potential to cause additional expenditure due to incorrect claims being paid – a scenario that should be avoided.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Housing Benefit applications have been decided locally for nearly 30 years, during which time the complexity in relation to regulations and legislation has grown significantly. Whilst the WLGA supports the principles of UC and its attempts to simplify regulations, it appears the decision making on housing costs will be far more limited than that which currently exists under Housing Benefit. Concern is therefore raised that a centralised model that is introduced in haste, with limited opportunity from LA experts, may result in contrived tenancy claims and multiple claims from properties being made with incorrectly awarded Housing Costs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.73pt; padding-left:6.62pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The WLGA supports the principles outlined in UC however it has serious concerns that the project will be delivered on schedule. It therefore suggests its approach outlined in this response helps to mitigate remaining risks to the Universal Credit project which will help to ensure its “safe landing” whilst allowing time for UC system development to be able to deal with the inclusion of housing costs at a later date if required. Local Authorities already make monthly payments to certain private tenants of Housing Benefit, and the proposal outlined in this document would allow this to be extended across different the social sector which helps to deliver one of the key aims of Welfare Reforms in giving customers the scope to manage their own affairs. This would help alleviate a number of the budgeting and money management issues which people may be faced in a sharp transition to UC. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>